639
00:43:59,380 --> 00:44:07,180
Scott: Because the software was free and open source, you didn't have to go and get the software from the person who made the software.

640
00:44:07,261 --> 00:44:07,510
Scott: You could.

641
00:44:08,824 --> 00:44:12,820
Scott: You could, but it was legal to redistribute the software.

642
00:44:13,921 --> 00:44:21,900
Scott: So distributions, Linux distributions, what a Linux distribution is, is basically someone who went out and picked a whole bunch of software.

643
00:44:22,080 --> 00:44:28,840
Scott: And they said, I have chosen this set of software to use together on top of the Linux kernel that I have also customized.

644
00:44:30,001 --> 00:44:31,747
Scott: Download this from me.

645
00:44:32,008 --> 00:44:35,480
Scott: You can just download all the software from me only and not from anyone else.

646
00:44:36,141 --> 00:44:44,240
Scott: And then I will maintain this repository of software, which is redistributed copies of the software.

647
00:44:44,361 --> 00:44:48,460
Scott: And I've prepared it all in such a way that it all goes together nicely.

648
00:44:49,083 --> 00:44:52,520
Scott: And you're going to update versions and apply security patches.

649
00:44:52,962 --> 00:44:58,340
Scott: And I'm going to maintain a cohesive ecosystem of software that all works together.

650
00:44:58,762 --> 00:44:58,962
Scott: Right.

651
00:44:59,123 --> 00:45:03,540
Scott: All the versions are in alignment with each other and all the libraries are, you know.

652
00:45:04,022 --> 00:45:07,120
Scott: And it's like they do all the work for you.

653
00:45:07,240 --> 00:45:17,520
